My feet have been on pavement for almost a week & it's starting to make me stir crazy. I often share my photos for other people's inspiration but the truth is more often than not I want to escape to these places just as much as you do.

I stood wide eyed staring at exhibit after exhibit at the American Museum of Natural History yesterday. Near the end I came to a large wall with this quote, "Treat the earth well: it was not given to you by your parents, it was loaned to you by your children."
.

It may be the most important thing I've read all year.

The blue hour - Many artists treasure this period for its quality of light. Its name comes from the French origin - l'heure bleue and It only lasts about 40 minutes on a clear day. It's that short period between early twilight or late dusk where the sun is so far past the horizon that it's radiance takes on a blue hue.
.

I didn't realize it actually had an incredibly scientific explanation until i looked it up on Wikipedia... mind blown

Nervous, excited & I can literally feel my heart beating through my chest. Tomorrow we premier "Under an Arctic Sky" at @tribeca film festival then kick off our Tour. Through this process I've gained a respect for any filmmaker that has ever gone through this.. there is no greater or worse feeling than putting your work out there.
.

We just released our first months worth of film Tour stops. We're  traveling the whole Western US including Canada. I would be honored to have you attend one of our film screenings + slideshows so I can share this film with you in person.
.

More stops are being added everyday including Midwest, East Coast, Europe, Aus, Iceland + many more later in summer/ fall. 
For Tickets check my bio link or www.UnderAnArcticSky.com/tour

The transition from a long winter to spring/ summer can be hard.  Here's an example of how to cope....beautifully demonstrated by @basillynch as he reintroduces his body to a little Vitamin D on a trip to the Golden Cathedral.
Aerial wave study on an isolated stretch of NZ coast. My first time shooting aerial photography, sometime around 2009.. I got hooked fast.

It's hard to describe the Joy of returning. I grew up traveling here a lot as a kid. One of my first rolls of film ever was shot here with my Grandpa. My dad is buried maybe an hour away.. in a cemetery outside Las Cruces. It has always been a little bitter sweet coming out this way. But age has given me perspective & confidence that I can put a lot of beauty out in the world. Photography has even helped heal some wounds I didn't really know were there. For me it has been so much more than just a career.. it's a tool to communicate. Some days it seems like the only language I know... or at least the one I'm the best at speaking.
.

I've been a bit obsessed with this photo series ..( as you can tell) but coming  back to see this place in its full glory with the platform to inspire others to see it for themselves is what it's all about for me.
No two dunes will ever be the same.

Those of you who purchased our calendar (thank you!) will turn over the page tomorrow to begin May with our sweet Creatch, Bella. I haven't been able to post about her since we lost her suddenly last December. I still think of and miss her terribly every day. But please do not be sad when you look at her judgmental but very cute face this month. I would rescue her all over again if I could, even if it meant losing her again too. She lived a good life, and will be forever remembered for her bad attitude, dislike of my son and puppies, costume changes, love of mud (and crap, and disgusting things...), her constant bark, occasional cuddles, and especially for her role as captain of the fun police. She can never be replaced. I'm sure she is barking, policing, and speaking street spanish over the rainbow bridge still üêä #sheddoitagainese üëÆ‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏èüöîüåà ‚ù§Ô∏è #rescuefamily #foreverinmyheart

Softest pup of them all. Total Bubba Gump lower lip/under bite ü¶ê *Our weirdo. He is scared of almost everything, including the wind, yet loves to eat the leaf blower. Today I am going to start a new photo series, a continuance from the #secretlifeofmisfits we did last year. Everyone has been pretty cute lately, ever developing their individual personalities no matter what age. I'll start with Lucky because - seniority... * Lucky Baller (AKC registered name, yes a rescue dog anyways) - turned 14 in February. Been with us since 9 months old. Did not get the memo that he's not 2 anymore. * Because of this lack of communication I am constantly having to protect him from himself. He still climbs stairs, chases cars, plays nonstop fetch, and inhales all of his food. * He has finally started showing signs of old man behavior lately. Basically, he does what he wants. He goes on self guided tours of the neighborhood (mostly our property), demands multiple middle of the night potty breaks (these last for what seems like an eternity each time), drinks water only from his stream, checks his strawberry patch many times daily (almost bud!), and actually goes inside on his own when he's tired sometimes (unbelievable). * He is just as obsessed with me as ever. If you want to know where mom is just look for Lucky. He is in the bathroom for every shower, and if I leave the room he follows even if it's just for a second. This makes me consider every time if it's really necessary or not to move so he doesn't have to. * I went out of town a few weeks ago and although the rest of the family was here, at bedtime he walked the house looking for me and crying. My daughter ended up having to sleep on the floor with him both nights. So, basically, I guess I'm not going anywhere anymore because that crushed me. * Lots of people ask where the strawberry üçì obsession came from. Really it's a food obsession in general, he's just discovered that there is a source and it's pretty much magic to him that they keep coming back. * Yes he's always yelling at me in pictures. He associates the camera with food and there is no time to waste when it comes to treats. 
#getinmybelly #notgettinganyyounger #timesawasting #idowhatiwant #rescuefamily * Up next, according to age order, is the magical Kilocorn ü¶Ñ

Photographer Ruman Hamdani (@theotherrumii) studied engineering in #Delhi, but he longed to go back home to #Srinagar, where he had spent his childhood. He found inspiration in his roots. "I would come back during the semester holidays and carry my camera everywhere," he remembers, "In Delhi, I would rarely use my camera." Of this image, he writes, "While I was walking along the #Jhelum River, this kid came out of his little makeshift house. As I pointed my camera, he ran back in and then came out again and went back again, not letting me take a picture. I lowered my camera and moved ahead. Knowing that he was curious, I quickly turned back and took the picture while he was checking if I had left." Follow along at @theotherrumii for more.

"I've grown to love the old part of #Srinagar, and I often do photo walks there," photographer Ruman Hamdani (@theotherrumii) tells us, "The people, the shrines, the architecture, everything takes you to a different era. As urbanization grows, the city is losing its traditional charm. I feel through my images, I can contribute to preserving our culture." He spotted this textile vendor on #Dal Lake. "His boat carried all kinds of cloth, mostly woolens, as it was winter," Hamdani writes, "As they were rowing ahead, I saw a lady walking along the bank bargaining over stitching charges with the vendor. The boat never stopped, but they seemed to make a deal." // #documentaryphotography #streetphotography #streetphoto #streetportrait #photostreet

"The more I traveled through #Kashmir, the more my desire to share its natural beauty with the world grew," photographer/filmmaker Ruman Hamdani (@theotherrumii) writes of his artistic beginnings, "In the beginning, I would use my father's phone to take pictures and later with a small point and shoot." Of this image, he writes, "The little shepherd boy was ¬†shy and preferred to tend to his sheep. While #Srinagar city is quickly getting modernized, many parts still present village-like scenes." // #documentaryphotography #contemporaryphotography #tinypeopleinbigplaces #landscapelovers #landscapecaptures #captivatingkashmir #indiapictures

Today's takeover is by photographer and filmmaker Ruman Hamdani (@theotherrumii), who grew up in #Srinagar, #India. "I was always drawn to beauty and spending time in nature, something I credit my father for," the artist writes, "We would often go to the various hill stations of #Kashmir. I loved observing these places and the lifestyle of the people who lived there." He spotted this pair fishing on #Nigeen Lake. "The reflections and the symmetry here were pleasing to the eyes," Hamdani remembers The two men were actually both on their phones, while their fishing rods were doing the work." // #contemporaryphotography #landscapephotography #landscapelovers #landscapecaptures #liveoutdoors #tinypeopleinbigplaces #documentaryphotography

‚ÄúOn assignment for National Geographic (@natgeo) in #Yellowstone National Park, I left my Montana motel while it was still dark outside," photojournalist David Guttenfelder (@dguttenfelder) told us recently, "I was driving towards a riverside pasture outside of town with a plan to standing in a field of grazing bison while the sun rose. But when the morning light came, ominous and richly red, I was trapped at a red traffic light behind rows of work commuters in #Bozeman. That morning, for Nat Geo, I‚Äôd failed. But the smartphone photo I shot, and posted to my Instagram account while still sitting at the intersection in my truck, remains my most 'liked' photo (with more than 30,000)." // #nationalpark #ontheroadagain #americanroads

'Praying for a Miracle' by Robin Hammond (@hammond_robin) has been named the Second Prize Single in the "People "Category at World Press Photo 2017 (@worldpressphoto). "Hellen Alfred lives with a mental health condition in #Juba, South Sudan. She says she fell ill after the birth of her sixth child," Hammond writes of this photo, "Mental illness in South Sudan is often attributed to witchcraft. This means the mentally ill are frequently ostracized and regarded as a danger to society. Juba has only a handful of qualified psychiatrists and psychologists, but international NGOs are working with the Sudanese authorities to improve conditions for the mentally ill." The work was commissioned by @noorimages for Handicap International. // #wPPh2017

We recently asked 6 photo editors to tell us how they use IG to find talent. Francesca Gennari of Burn Magazine (@burnmagazine), told us, "I use it daily‚Äîit‚Äôs very important to be always connected. Instagram uses a language that is much more immediate and allows you to understand how a photographer ‚Äòsees‚Äô‚Äîit often tells you more about a photographer than a photo essay." This image is from the series ‚ÄòSin and Salvation in Baptist Town‚Äô by Matt Eich (@matteich), which Gennari found via IG. Of the work, Eich writes, "For the last 4 years I have been drawn to #Greenwood, #Mississippi like a moth to a flame. I have explored a complex intersection of issues that span race, class, joblessness, opportunity, housing, education and segregation."

Scarlett Hooft Graafland took this photograph on the shores of Belo sur Mer in #Madagascar, using local fishermen and their canoes as her subject. In each canoe, you can see the knees of a fisherman poking out. When traveling to remote and often harsh landscapes, Hooft Graafland gets to know the local community and collaborates with them closely to make her surreal scenes. 'Discovery', the artist's solo exhibition at Flowers Gallery (@flowersgallery) in #London, is on view through today, Saturday, April 29th. All images on view are printed directly from the artist's negatives. // #fineartphotography #contemporaryphotography #belosumer #landscapelovers #analoguevibes #analogphotography #tinypeopleinbigplaces

In 1946, the same year he took this photograph at #6thAvenue in #NYC, the great photographer #ToddWebb wrote the following in his journal: ‚ÄúI am full of things to do, and I have no spare time on my hands. It seems like a very good life. I am broke. But what the hell, you can‚Äôt have everything.‚Äù Before he found success as a photographer, Webb had been a stockbroker, a gold prospector, and a forest ranger. He wrote stories, though they were never published. He served in the Second World War. Now, his photographs are being show in two exhibitions: 'City Seen' at The Museum of the City of New York (@museumofcityny) and 'Down Any Street' at The Curator Gallery (@thecuratorgallery). Learn more at @toddwebbarchive. // #silvergelatin #streetphoto

Surreal self-portraitist Izumi Miyazaki is one of the 40 female photographers spotlighted in 'Girl on Girl: Art and Photography in the Age of the Female Gaze', a new book by writer/curator Charlotte Jansen (@omfgnoway). In the book, the artist touches on the expectation of women to be "kawaii" (meaning "cute"). She herself often chooses to be "kowai" (meaning "scary") instead. "I have no special message or purpose when I take photos," Miyazaki told @CNN last summer, "I only hope that visitors approach my photography with an open mind -- with as much freedom of thinking as I try to have when I create a picture." Head on over to publisher Lawrence King (@laurencekingpub) to get your copy of 'Girl on Girl.' // #femalegaze #selfportrait

Scarlett Hooft Graafland photographed this 11-year-old boy on the island of #Malekula in #Vanuatu. As with elements in many of the artists photograph, the yellow ship in his arms references the place's history. The ship is a model of HMS Resolution, the preferred ship of 18th century Captain James Cook. "The boy is a descendant of the chief of the tribe that welcomed Captain Cook to the island, two and a half centuries ago, when Cook‚Äôs ship laid at anchor at the same spot," Hooft Graafland explains in the image's caption. This photo and others from the artist's many travels are on view at Flowers Gallery (@flowersgallery) in #London through today. // #ScarlettHooftGraafland #fineartphotography #contemporaryphotograph

The late photographer #ToddWebb (@toddwebbarchive) was friends with #WalkerEvans, #GordonParks, #AnselAdams, #LisetteModel, #BereniceAbbott, and #AlfredStieglitz and Georgia O‚ÄôKeeffe. "They drank together, ate together, traveled together, worked together," curator Bill Shapiro writes, "But while the others became stars, Webb took himself off that path." Shapiro has since gotten to know Webb through his journal entries. ‚ÄúEverybody should know his name," the curator says. 'Down Any Street: Todd Webb‚Äôs Photographs of New York 1946-1960' at The Curator Gallery (@thecuratorgallery) is on view now. Shapiro's exhibition coincides with 'City Seen', a large Todd Webb retrospective at The Museum of the City of New York (@museumofcityny).

I am working on a @natgeo Jaguar story. Here is Scarface running after a caiman which he did not get this time. Jaguars are the 3rd largest of the big cats. Found from US / Mexico border to northern Argentina. Jaguars have rebounded in this area where 95% of the land is privately owned. In the past many ranchers would kill the cats when they ate their cattle. Today in this area tourism brings in much more money to the local economy than cattle ranching. So the jaguar population is increasing. But revenge killings of jaguars happen close to this area and all throughout the jaguars range. Also poaching for skins, bones and teeth is growing for the first time since the 1970‚Äôs to feed the demand for Asian Traditional Medicine and luxury items from endangered species. ‚ÄúWhen the buying stops, the killing can too.‚Äù @wildaid @bertiegregory

My first story with big cats was the 1st @natgeo Jaguar story 20 years ago! It has changed my life working with the magical and magnificent cats of the world. Animals have emotions just like we have-kids hang out and play like these 2 cubs.. Forests provide us with up to 50% of the oxygen we breathe - oceans the rest. They give us 75% of the fresh water.
If we can save the forest of the Amazon and other areas in Central and South America for the JAGUAR and Puma. The forests of Central Africa for the leopard, lion, elephants etc. And the forests of South Asia for the Tigers and Leopards. If you save the top predator in any ecosystem you save everything that lives with them.
So if - We Save Big Cats we can help Save Ourselves.  Please visit CauseAnUproar.org to find out other ways to become involved to save big cats!

I am excited to bring my NG LIVE presentation, ‚ÄúOn the Trail of Big Cats‚Äù to @natgeo‚Äôs Grosvenor Theater in Washington DC on April 13th! 
Please come to hear about my life and work with Jaguars, Snow Leopards, Cougars and Tigers!!
Snow leopards are the ghosts of the high mountain areas of central Asia in which they live.
The areas in which SL‚Äôs live are vitally important as they provide water for 100‚Äôs of millions of people.
But the glaciers that provide the water are rapidly disappearing, which begs the question - what will the future bring for people and animals?

Local people need to benefit from living with predators - snow leopards are persecuted by revenge killings - when they kill someone‚Äôs livestock 
a herder will then kill them. There are great community conservation projects where local herders can protect their flocks, making more money and saving snow leopards at the same time! Turning and economic negative into an economic positive - and saving snow leopards at the same time!

Please visit National Geographic‚Äôs Big Cat Initiative @ CauseAnUproar.org, to find out ways to become involved - to save big cats!

Water is life - we are the water planet. Tuesday was World Water Day. 
Here is a man bathing in the river at the end a very hot day. 
Shot for the @natgeo story on the Irrawaddy River.
We humans often forget that without the vital necessities our planet gives us - like WATER we would no longer survive.
The water we drink and use to grow food - is also responsible for 1/2 of our oxygen.
The water we drink and the air we breathe is all here for us every moment of everyday. Though we take it all for granted 
as we do the natural ecosystems which provide these life life giving elements.
the oceans and the forests give us the water we drink and the air we breathe.
50% of the oxygen comes from forests and grasslands - where the big cats live.
50 % of the rest of the oxygen comes from the oceans - WATER!! Though we cut down our forests and pollute and remove the vital creatures which keep
our seas in balance. 75% of fresh water comes from forests and grasslands. Forests pull carbon from the atmosphere and slow climate change, and give homes
to the creatures that live within. If we can save big cats we can help save ourselves.
Water is life.

Women bring their tea leaves to be weighed at the end of the day on the edge of Kaziranga National Park. In many areas of the world the economy is run by women, though they do not benefit the same as men. When women run local economies-children benefit.

Kaziranga is an incredible diversity of life - the area has the largest population of Indian one horned rhinos, Asian Elephants and wild water buffalo left in the world. And the highest density of tigers found anywhere in the world. It is a ‚Äúhistoric landscape‚Äù where tigers live as in centuries past - with many species listed above that are gone from other tiger reserves. A Jewel in the Crown of India.

"You will never have to force anything that's truly meant to be." üåø Just weeks before our trip to Maui, I connected with @ellenfisher on Instagram. So that‚Äôs the story how I meant to meet Ellen Fisher. Take a look at her account, watch her YouTube videos and give her a follow. Good morning mister turtle! I don't think anyone quite understands how much I love cruising around with turtles underwater. The fact that Jewels and I had both separately stumbled across this guy and ended up together was the best. We literally cruised with him for an hour and I loved every minute of it. This was Lakeside, a popular snorkeling site in the national park and your best bet of seeing turtles on the fringing reef in Ningaloo. @WesternAustralia #JustAnotherDayInWA

Good morning!! So although I'm getting ready to do my conference today I'm also still posting shots from Western Australia and Ningaloo. These guys main job is to spot whale sharks from the air but they moonlight offering scenic flights. @WesternAustralia #JustAnotherDayInWA

So you know what it's like when you have like a million photos of whale sharks and that's all you want to post but you also want to share all these other stories and places too? Anyone? I love a good sunset on the West Coast of Oz, there's nothing like watching the sun going down over the ocean. @WesternAustralia #JustAnotherDayInWA

We are back to Western Australia! üòçüòçüòç This month has been kind of all over the place for me but I'm back on track now and I have heaps of photos to share from Perth and Exmouth. This is one of my favorite shots taken of the whale shark experience on Live Ningaloo. I went in the water with only a fish eye lens so even when the whale shark looks far away, like here, it was actually incredibly close. All of my underwater photography at Ningaloo was shot on the Olympus E-M1 Mark II and my spanking new underwater housing. @WesternAustralia #JustAnotherDayInWA

I am interrupting my Western Australia shots to share exactly what I am doing right now but don't worry, I have photos for days right now and it will all get posted. üòÇüòÇ I'm in Jakarta! I really had to share this photo of Turquoise Bay, even though shooting conditions weren't great when I shot it. Good morning! This is Mandu Mandu Gorge at sunrise, one of the very popular activities on offer at Sal Salis. We had a 5:30 start to ascend to the top of the trail in time for sunrise and it was worth it. I didn't love it that Jayde, Jewels and I were totally beaten on the trail by a seven year old, he must have been half a km away from us at all times. Right, time to start exercising again. üòÇüòÇ @WesternAustralia #JustAnotherDayInWA

I promised aerials didn't I? Here's the first! So one of the coolest things about swimming with whale sharks in Ningaloo is that every single boat on the water has a plane up in the air doing all the hard work of locating the animals. (Not a plane per boat, usually one for every 3-4 boats.) These 'spotter' planes are piloted by amazing pilots such as Tiffany and Jacob from Ningaloo Aviation. Not only do they spot whale sharks but they also offer scenic flights and this would be a huge recommendation from me! Jewels and I were incredibly fortunate to go up for two flights, one during the day to see whale sharks and one for sunset. If you look closely at this shot you can actually see the eco tents of Sal Salis and how well they blend into their surroundings, nice location hey? Thanks @NingalooAviation #JustAnotherDayInWA

Good morning!!! I'm sure a few people by now are wondering what Sal Salis actually looks like and I do have a few shots of the place and some aerials too. This is from inside one of the eco-tents, isn't it so cute?! The entire place has only 15 tents so the maximum number of guests is usually 30 but there's always some kids kicking around too, they get to sleep in swags inside or outside. üò± When you check in you are thoroughly briefed on how it all works, i.e. There is a nature toilet (no flush) and the water allocation for showers is 20L per guest per day. Of course Jewels and I had to have a photo shoot, the #JewLau creativity came out big time. üòÇüòÇüòÇ I loved this sunset session. üî•üò≥üíÉüèºüåû @WesternAustralia #JustAnotherDayInWA

Before I tell you anything else about this photo I just want to mention that we had "bad" conditions in Ningaloo! That's right, this is what bad, windy, choppy conditions look like! üò±üòÇüê† As you know I was staying at Sal Salis and all activities are included when you stay, with the exception of swimming with the whale sharks. The team all get together every afternoon to decide what activities best suit the conditions for the next day and then they write a handful of options up on the chalkboard for you to put your name down for. So, on day two we chose to snorkel at Lake Side and Jewels and I found a turtle and basically stayed by its side for an hour and a half. I seriously couldn't love turtles more, they're like the grumpy old men of the sea. The funniest thing was that Jewels and I found this guy independently of each other and when I stuck my head out to tell Jewels I noticed she was right next to me, she did the same thing. Awww üòÑüòùü§ó @SalSalisNingaloo #JustAnotherDayInWA

Omg, yesterday's whale shark post made me so happy and I promise I'm still catching up on comments. I wrote until my hands were sore and I was falling asleep! As I mentioned I've been at Sal Salis, @salsalisningaloo if you want to check them out, and it's been an amazing stay. Sal Salis has just been accepted into Luxury Lodges of Australia and it has to be one of the most incredible places I've stayed. Not only is the property beautiful but you can feel great for staying there because the entire camp is an ecotourism development camp. You'll sleep in a wilderness tent with an eco toilet, no air conditioning and limited daily water but I swear I've never been more comfortable. Also, don't even get me started on the food and wine and activities. This is a shot from my last night after quite a few wines over dinner. üòÇüòÇ I always seem to do star shots better that way. üôàüç∑ @WesternAustralia #JustAnotherDayInWA

I'm back and OMFG OMFG! Jewels and I teased that we were going offline for a few days and this is why! Bucket list dream has been ticked off ... swimming with whale sharks in Ningaloo. Although there is obviously service in the area we have just spent three incredible nights at Sal Salis (digital detox!) and also did a full day out on their own boat, "Live Ningaloo", the only boat operating in the area that takes just ten guests at a time. I have an incredible amount of images to share from the whale sharks and the last few days here on Australia's largest fringing reef. All underwater images have been shot on Olympus. This image is an incredibly rare shot, whale sharks are solitary animals and only interact with other whale sharks when they literally collide in the water. I died, literal death! You can imagine how Jewels was. üòÇüòÇüê≥üíô @WesternAustralia #JustAnotherDayInWA

So true @thinkgrowprosper!
As we go through life, we often accumulate beliefs, subconscious mental programs, and emotional baggage that does not belong to us. They were passed down to us by someone else.
-
Maybe it was a negative comment from someone that planted a seed of doubt in your mind. Maybe it was an offhand remark from a parent who unintentionally instilled a limiting belief in you. Or perhaps it was a "friend" who intentionally tried to hold you back by making you believe you weren't good enough somehow.
-
Understand that these types of interactions are usually a reflection of how others perceive themselves and not an accurate assessment of your true abilities or worth.
-
Let go of what isn't yours. Take inventory of your beliefs and the mental patterns you follow without even thinking. Do they belong to you? Or did you unwittingly inherent them from someone else?
‚ÄîRuben

About a week ago I broke the Boulder paragliding site distance record, and at the end of a gorgeous 4 hour flight found myself 100kilometers away near the border of Wyoming!  It's not a crazy proud record by modern paragliding standards, but I'm still really stoked to have it for the time being, and it's wild to think how much I've learned in the last two years of obsessive paragliding!  If you haven't already, please check out my film The Fledglings Uncut, which documents the early stages of my paragliding adventures with @mattsegal ...the link to the film is in my profile.  Also thanks to everyone who has supported the film so far!  @thenorthface #skycrack. This is a more recent photo I grabbed of my buddy Josh Finkelstein flying the Boulder site where I snagged the record.

Two days ago I had one of my most outrageous paragliding flights yet!  I launched from Glenwood Springs, and flew over 80k, all the way to Vail using just nylon, string, and thermals!  Big thanks to @sendinglife for guiding me through the technical part of the flight before disappearing on his own 100k vision quest!  The views were other worldly, and the experience surreal.  Spring is respected and sometimes feared by paragliding pilots, because this is the time of year when some of the strongest, most rowdy thermals can be found.  At times I was being ripped into the sky at over 1100 feet a minute!  Wow! @thenorthface @fiveten_official #skycrack

That one time @mattsegal and I flew off of this!!!...the highest peak in Mexico!! full Uncut Fledglings Film is now available for download!  As seen At the Banff and @mountainfilm festivals!  Link in profile, or google The Fledglings Uncut!  If you liked The Sufferfest films,this is like Sufferfest with more danger and nylon!!! @thenorthface @pickybars #skycrack

One more from the Valle de los Condores in Chile of @alexhonnold on a wildly steep and classic  7c.  What are my chances of doing it first try I asked my buddy @mattsegal who had just lowered down from the route?? He responded, "not very good!" Alex concurred! I hand-jammed, or knee-barred almost every move, but I didn't fall!  Thanks for the confidence guys!! Haha! üòú

Some of the talented faces of my recent trip to Chile where much hard climbing was dispatched by this motley crew!!...including @alexandermegos making quick work of what is now Chiles hardest sport route. In order left to right starting at the top... 1: Chilean supermodel crusher  @soholangbehn 2: Megos coach and trainer to the stars "Dicky". 3: Brazil's hardest climber @felipe.camargo 4: American treasure @emilyaharrington 5: The wildly handsome Chilean climber @faculangbehn 6: The quirky cow-eyed @alexhonnold  7: The trad-master @mattsegal 8: and last but not least by Tendon strength and lock off  measures...@alexandermegos  who has the sense of humor of a Brit but with an unfortunate German accent üòúThanks @thenorthfacechile and @thenorthface for the awesome trip!

Warning!!! If you are in the SLC area this coming weekend @alexhonnold and I are going to be speaking at the Ogden Climbing Festival about how amazing, strong and handsome we are.  Get yourself tickets!  Now please enjoy this photograph from Chile of our campfire under the Milky Way! @thenorthface @blackdiamond
@mau_huerta pulling down in Chile!  @mau_huerta is one of Mexico's strongest climbers, and more importantly, he's a super nice dude! üëäüí™ @thenorthface @thenorthfacechile

Columns on columns! A little shot I took two days ago at the absolutely wild Valle de los Condores of @alexhonnold on his first ever free solo!  He might get good at this if he sticks with it!  Big thanks to @thenorthfacechile and @thenorthface for bringing me down for a whirlwind week of fun adventure and climbing.  I think Santiago has the most psyched climbers per capita of any place I've ever been!!

Photo by @csylvia508 of me doing my best competition climber impression while I'm here in Santiago Chile for the @thenorthface masters of bouldering competition, which is the largest climbing event in Latin America!  I was here to help commentate and to do a little slideshow, but I figured I might as well try my hand at the qualifiers.  I'm happy to say I didn't get dead last, though I was close üòú. Santiago has the most stoked strong young climbers per capita that I have ever seen!  Now we are headed to a climbing area called Valle de los Condores to do some traditional and sport climbing with an epic crew including, @alexandermegos @kilifish @emilyaharrington @mattsegal @alexhonnold and myself!  Woohooo!

@james_lucas aka, peaches, aka the climber formerly known as the "Last Dirtbag"... crushes 5.12 like it was a grape.  He was living in his Saturn station wagon ..until he got a job at @climbingmagazine and soon after a hot boulderite girlfriend who climbs double digits.  James is one of the world's few red point free-soloists, an honor he earned after decking from 100 feet off of the north overhang in J-tree, and then coming back a year later to successfully solo it.  James went on to free climb el cap in a day after that...but he has so much metal in him, he shits himself when you turn on the microwave!! But seriously, James is an inspiring dude!

For almost two years now, this guy, @tay.keating has been my collaborative partner in crime.  He's filmed all kinds of antics, and he's edited his ass off here in the illustrious office space of Cedar Wright Productions...that is my basement!  We've created some awesome stuff together, including The Fledglings which is touring the world, and our best film Safety 3rd with @bradgobright is coming very soon!  In the last year Taylor's flown off an 18000 foot volcano in a tandem Paraglider, open bivied in lion country, and generally enjoyed the full fledged Cedar sandbag... which some like to call "getting Cedared." Today is Taylor's birthday, so wish him luck... he's going to need it!

An oldie but goodie photo of me from Andrew McGarry who is living off the grid, without...gasp...social media..., somewhere in Hawaii!  @renan_ozturk and I thought we wee on a full first ascent until we found an old Banditos bolt hanger high on the wall.  We freed the route at 5.11+ but not before I accidentally dropped one of my climbing shoes off the wall!  Luckily Renan wore the same size as me, and we zipped his left shoe down the tag line each pitch, so we could finish the route all free!  Ha!  @thenorthface @fiveten_official @bluewaterropes

Valle de Bravo Mexico, a place so amazing they should bill a wall around it to keep the gringos out!  Here @mattsegal wanders around in the rising air under his trusty Paraglider!  The sun sets later if you take to the sky!  Rad trip with flying legends @nicgreece and @jeffreyshapiro

Never before seen photo of up and coming climber @alexhonnold getting mildly scared on the best free route on The Cat in Samburu country in Kenya.  Granted it's the only route on the formation, and involves aggressive attack wasps, and huge petrified bird shit jugs, but I swear it's a classic!!! @thenorthface

This is my full time valentine @nmilfeld who has made my life about a zillion times better.  In the last year she's done big wall linkups in Zion, climbed 5.13r trad in Eldo, ran a 50k ultra, looked dead sexy...etc...all while holding down a full time job as a Public Defender, and putting up with my antics... which is also a full time job.  Love you to the ends of the earth honey!!!

There's something missing hereüòú....An arm and two legs to be exact!  I had a fun night hanging out with @moinmountains James Scheri, and Craig DeMartino from @paradoxsports  Paradox is a rad climbing community of people with and without disabilities, that are working together to make climbing more accessible for people who might be blind, missing limbs, or even in a wheelchair!  My life has been made immeasurably better by my love for climbing, and for a veteran with a traumatic injury, someone coming back from a catastrophic car accident, or somebody recovering from limb loss because of cancer, a good old fashioned climbing gym session can be just as if not more life changing in such a wonderful way!  I really encourage folks to check out @paradoxsports and get involved, and or donate a little cash to the cause!  @thenorthface

I spent the last week in Valle de Bravo Mexico participating in the Monarca Open paragliding competition.  I learned a ton, and hope someday I can compete at the top level in this wonderfully outrageous, fringe sport.  For now I got a solid middle of the pack placing in my category.  Racing Paraglider's down complicated and committing  courses marked by GPS delineated goalposts, using only the invisible rising air of thermals to make forward progress is one of my newest passion/obsessions for sure!  Here my buddy Josh Finkelstein glides over Valle's lake, the goal for many of last weeks flights!  I may or may not have landed twenty feet from the shore one day, destroying my iPhone and my pride!  Ha.

A popular filming location for many western motion pictures, especially those by director John Ford, Monument Valley even has a location in the park named "John Ford Point." Many people mistakenly think that Monument Valley is a national park, but it is actually a Navajo Park controlled and operated by the Navajo Nation. Photos of the park‚Äôs world-famous panoramic views can be taken from the parking lot of the visitor center. Or for a more in-depth experience of the entire park, take a tour with a Navajo guide. You can explore Monument Valley and the Four Corners region by renting and driving an @AlamoRentACar from Durango, CO or Flagstaff, AZ.

#AlamoDriveHappy #MoreMemoriesPerGetaway #ad

A slot canyon located on Navajo land outside of Page, Arizona, Antelope Canyon may be one of the most photogenic places in the United States, if not the entire world. The light inside the canyon is simply incredible, and it is one of the few places where you want to photograph in the middle of the day when the sun is highest so you can capture the sun rays coming straight down. You can get to Page, AZ by renting and driving your @AlamoRentACar from Durango, CO or Flagstaff, AZ.  While in Page, you can also explore Glen Canyon and the majestic Horseshoe Bend in the Colorado River.

#AlamoDriveHappy #MoreMemoriesPerGetaway #ad #arizona #antelopecanyon #navajo

Though one of the smaller national parks in the United States, Bryce Canyon National Park is certainly one of the most inspiring. Technically speaking, Bryce Canyon isn't a canyon at all, but a natural amphitheater. The hoodoos in the amphitheater are erosional formations, which you can walk through on the many trails in the park. Sunrise in Bryce Canyon just might be the most spectacular in the National Park system. Rent a car from @AlamoRentACar and drive to Bryce Canyon from Las Vegas, NV or Flagstaff, AZ.

#AlamoDriveHappy #MoreMemoriesPerGetaway #ad #nps101 #utah #brycecanyon #nps101 #nationalparks

Fly into Las Vegas, book your @AlamoRentACar and drive approximately three hours north to explore everything Zion has to offer. ‚Ä®#AlamoDriveHappy #MoreMemoriesPerGetaway #ad

Skellig Michael was always one of my favorite places in Europe. Thankfully, I was able to go before Star Wars: The Force Awakens was released.

Before Star Wars, few people knew about Skellig Michael and demand to visit was rather low. Since then, demand to visit the island has sky rocketed, but the number of available boats and seats hasn‚Äôt increased very much. Toss in the regular rain and weather cancelations which are a reality in that part of the Atlantic, and it is now become very difficult to visit.

If you visit Skellig Michael (which I highly recommend) I suggest booking your trip well in advance, and possibly give yourself an extra day incase the boat is delayed due to weather. Also, even if there isn‚Äôt a delay, you will want to prepare for rain which is quite likely.

If you‚Äôve seen the new trailer for Star Wars: The Last Jedi, there is a whole lot more Skellig Michael, which means it is only going to get more popular, which means you probably need to double down on my advice in 2018.

Last October I visited the tiny island nation of Tuvalu.

Tuvalu is the smallest country which is a member of the United Nations, with a population of less than 10,000. It is also one of the smallest countries in the world by area at only 26 km¬≤.

I spent four days on the Funafuti atoll, which is the capital and most populated island in Tuvalu.‚Ä®‚Ä®There isn‚Äôt a whole lot to do in Tuvalu. In addition to being tiny, it is also the least visited country in the world. The only way to reasonably get there is by an expensive flight from Fiji, and it is expensive because Air Fiji has a monopoly on the route.‚Ä®‚Ä®The airstrip is right in the middle of the island with roads and people going over it all day long. When a plane lands, there is a big production with sirens and trucks to make sure that no one is on the runway.

I took this photo when I rented a scooter one day and drove from one end of the island to the other. This is taken at one of the extreme ends of Funafuti where few people live.

In the city of Kyoto, Japan you can find the Fushimi Inari Taisha shrine which lies on the Inari mountain. It is the primary shrine to Inari, which in the Shinto religion is the god of industry, prosperity and success.

The shine in Kyoto is noteworthy for the hundreds of orange tori, or gates, which line the path up the mountain. The tori are donated by businesses who seek good fortune.

As the tori are made of wood, they are always being replaced and are always under construction.

The shrine can be easily visited as there is a Japan Rail station at the base of the mountain.

I'm really excited to start sharing images from one of my favorite parks to photograph, Arches National Park in #Utah. I've photographed in Arches many times, so I know it well. It's not a big park, and everything is pretty easily accessed, so it is a ton of fun to be there with a camera. There are great shots and vantage points at almost every turn, but I always try to find new ones with each visit. This shot, of Delicate Arch, is from across the canyon looking back the Arch. I think people often overlook the cool things that can be found just outside of the national parks. For instance, we found this really cool volcanic plug, nicknamed The Needle, outside of Black Canyon of the Gunnison. A "plug" is a volcanic object that is created when magma hardens within a vent of an active volcano. This one stands about 800 feet tall and was formed some 28 million years ago. This is a pretty neat thing to stumble upon when playing around in the parks. It serves as a good reminder to keep your eyes peeled and always be open to new and different exploration. You just may find something really cool. ‚Ä¢

Most of the cliffside dwellings I saw at Mesa Verde seemed pretty easy to navigate to/from. They all included a bit of climbing and scrambling, but seemed doable. However, every once in a while we'd come upon one that just confounded me as to how they not only built these houses in the crevices, but climbed to them carrying food, water, and even children in their backs. Turns out, they carved footholds and handholds into the rock walls that allowed them to scramble up and down vertical cliffs. I think I too would rest pretty soundly at night knowing what any visitors/enemies had to go through just to reach my house. I may, however, have nightmares from time to time thinking about climbing down the walls! ‚Ä¢

Kiva is a Hopi word meaning "ceremonial room". The Kiva is roughly the ancestral puebloan equivalent to today's temple, synagogue, mosque, or church. All Kivas have a small hole near the firepit, called a Sipapu, which a Hopi word which means "place of emergence". It was believed that this small hole was a gateway to the spiritual world. Most of the Kivas you'll see at Mesa Verde are round in shape. However, at one of the Far View sites (Coyote Village along the top of the Mesa) you can find this really interesting keyhole shape. Nobody really knows why the keyhole shape came about just in this one complex, nor why it didn't continue as they later moved down below the cliffs. What's your theory why they used this keyhole shape for a brief moment in time?
‚Ä¢
Mesa Verde National Park (48 of 59)

Mesa Verde, in southwest Colorado, blew me away. Home to some 600 or so Ancestral Puebloan cliff dwellings that were inhabited from AD 600 to 1300, I had no idea the extent nor the beauty of these cultural wonders. Most of the dwellings contains less than 5 rooms, but the masterpiece of the national park lies in the huge dwelling called Cliff Palace. The largest cliff dwelling in North America, Cliff Palace has 150 rooms, 23 Kivas (underground ceremonial pits), and housed approximately 100 people. It was a thriving community in its heyday and when you walk among the ruins you can still feel their haunting presence and experience what it must have been like to live here. Truly an incredible place. ‚Ä¢
Mesa Verde National Park (48 of 59)

Instagram can be a lot of things, but I think it's safe to say that all of us use it to find inspiration (among other things). I spent way too much time last night searching for just that:: inspiration. Surfing hashtags, clicking on photo tags, hunting for new accounts and clicking on old ones too in order to find something that piqued my interest or curiosity.
üíó
It's a very fine line I think -- to find just the right dose or (rather) "kind" of inspiration that motivates rather than discourages (or leaves me feeling inferior, hopeless, umm not-pretty-enough, or discontent with how God made me?)
üíó
BUT I think the 'right' (the good) kind Of inspiration is that which ENERGIZES us to live a better life (whatever that may mean for you). The BEST kind of inspiration makes us want to get off the couch and go work out OR wake up 10 minutes earlier so we can pack a lunch for work (to eat better!), have a quiet time, or (actually) finish blow drying our hair before work. The BEST kind of inspiration motivates, energizes, and excites us! It GALVANIZES us to move, do something, and believe that we can be and do better! Don't you think?
üíó
THAT BEING SAID, What inspires you? Better yet, WHO inspires you? Tag actual people OR even things if you want, OR tell me about that song or book that's inspiring you right now!
üíó
Comment with your answer and/or tag your fave accounts (could be calligraphy, art, faith, fitness, food, ANYTHING) that inspire YOU to live a BETTER & more ABUNDANT life in any way. Don't hold back, friends ‚ò∫Ô∏è

reflections | last night I had a moment I'll never forget... I was having kind of a down week, but one of my friends had an extra pass for the last day of coachella. there's been a lot of things I haven't been able to do since breaking my wrist, physically and financially. thank god, shooting is something I've been able to manage. a couple months ago, I couldn't snap my fingers or clap my hands. I couldn't turn the ignition over to start my car, or turn the dial for the ac. fast forward to last night. I was dancing my heart out to jai wolf's set. then it hit me. hands in the air, I was snapping and clapping my hands to the beat. this moment made me so happy. it was a reminder of how much progress I've made. I'm still on the road to recovery, but I'm so thankful for the little things along the way. we all get knocked down, but it's our choice to either be defeated or get back up. I don't know about you... but when something breaks me, I'm going to get back up and I'm going to dance.
thank you for all the love and support on my last post. you are my light.
